title: For Sale/Trade:  ww1 walther model 4 .32 acp
postcontent:
I am selling for $500 or for trade for a handgun of equal value,,my familys walther pistol in .32acp , early ww1 1st production pistol!
The Model 4 is a relatively simple handgun of blowback design, with a fixed barrel, an external extractor, and a concealed hammer. Its most unusual feature is that (like its predecessor the Model 3) its extractor and ejection port are on the left. The barrel acts as a guide for the concentric recoil spring, which is held in place by a bayonette-type lug that covers the front of the barrel, and by a sleeve at the rear which also serves to cover the spring. When the slide moves rearward, it forces the trigger bar down, disconnecting it from the sear. The safety is a rotating thumb lever that positively locks the cocked hammer. There is a screw on the backstrap of the grip that regulates the tension of the flat hammer spring. The gun is well-balanced, fits the hand very nicely, and points instinctively. It is also reasonably accurate.
There is absolutely no play in the fitment of the slide and receiver. The gun is spot-on at 25 to 50 yards. The trigger pull is rather heavy and the gun has considerable recoil. Recoil causes the trigger guard to batter my trigger finger, making it sore after a couple of magazines, so I prefer to shoot the gun with a glove on. Nevertheless, the grip fits my hand perfectly and it points better than any gun except the Remington Model 51. The slide does not stay back on the last round, and there is no provision for locking it open. The gun lacks a magazine safety and may be fired without a magazine. The thumb safety is very easy to disengage, but it is more secure than that of the 1910 Browning,bore and crown are exelent, rifleing is strong, great action.fun shooter .ya might wanna make this one a safe queen,the finish is still almost all there it fires fine and has a nice pop to it, i will trade for a semi auto of equal value or sell for $500 no lowball offers please . must be of age and present state i.d

postcontent: Looking for a landowner near Lexington (Frankfort/Winchester/Georgetown/Harrodsburg, etc.) who would be open to hosting an Appleseed marksmanship clinic on their farm or property. There is no cost for hosting this event, which consists of two days of intense shooting instruction by the best rifle marksmanship and firearm safety instructors in the nation. Appleseed is an all-volunteer 501(c)(3) organization dedicated to awakening the Rifleman that lives inside every American through history and marksmanship education, and is affiliated with the Revolutionary War Veterans Association. Distance needed is a minimum of 25 meters. Longer distances would be a bonus. A good embankment/backstop is required for safety. For more information about hosting a shoot, please go to http://www.appleseedinfo.org/host_appleseed.html For general Appleseed info, go to http://www.appleseedinfo.org/index.html You can also contact me for more information about the program.

title: For Sale:  Fulton Armory NM M14S & Lots of Extras
postcontent:
(There have been questions about the brass & dies. If you don't reload I can leave it out and adjust the price. If you just want the reloading components, make an offer on them.)

This is Fulton’s conversion of a Polytech M14s. Essentially everything but the forged, not cast, receiver was replaced. It is a heck of a shooter but when I got this done in 1999 I realized my eyes weren’t up using a serious match rifle. I took it to two matches and never used it much as shown by that unopened bag of brass.
The bore is excellent. Some of the white/yellow stuff in the pictures is the tetra grease.

Here is what Futon did:
Polytech Upgrade: Replace Hammer & sear, complete bolt 7790186 TRW ZJ, Op Rod 7267064 HRA, rear sight complete, NM flash suppressor without bayo lug (The was a ban on.), NM front sight,  reparkerized, op rod spring, NM spring guide, gas lock, op rod guide & pin, as system, connector lock, barrel, buffer, hammer pin.

Upgrade to medium weight barrel – marked Fulton Armory, NM gas system, NM aperture (rear sight), NM trigger. It was put in a GI fiberglass stock. The hole on the rear right is the missing naughty bits.

There are lots & lots of extras:

11 Twenty round mags, 4 never used by me but all surplus. I believe I bought these before the 94 ban since I had a reweld then.
2 5 round mags, came with rifle.

It has a Bushnell Sportview scope and mount. This had been on it before the conversion.

IMI Match 308 brass. One bag is unopened, I believe with 500 pieces. The other bag is once fired with 223 pieces.

A set of 3 Dillon dies and a Redding die.

A couple of books on the M14.

I’m not really interested in trades. Maybe for a small part of it but mainly cash.

I don't know how to do links here but if you can paste the next line into your browser you'll get an album of high res pictures:
http://s1119.photobucket.com/albums/k629/OldGeezerStuff/M14s/
